      "bar.outer P⟫ := by\n  sorry\n\nlemma Differentiable.rotprojRM (S : ℝ³) :\n    Differentiable ℝ fun (x : ℝ³)  ↦ (_root_.rotprojRM (x 1) (x 2) (x 0)) S := by\n  unfold _root_.rotprojRM\n  sorry\n\n@[fun_prop]\nlemma Differentiable.rotproj_inner (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) : Differentiable ℝ (rotproj_inner S w) :=\n  Differentiable.inner ℝ (Differentiable.rotprojRM S) (by fun_prop)\n\n/--\nAn explicit formula for the full derivative of rotproj_inner as a function ℝ³ → ℝ\n-/\nnoncomputable\ndef rotproj_inner' (pbar : Pose) (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) : ℝ³ →L[ℝ] ℝ :=\n  let grad : Fin 3 → ℝ := ![\n    ⟪pbar.rotR' (pbar.rotM₁ S), w⟫,\n    ⟪pbar.rotR (pbar.rotM₁θ S), w⟫,\n    ⟪pbar.rotR (pbar.rotM₁φ S), w⟫\n  ]\n  EuclideanSpace.basisFun (Fin 3) ℝ |>.toBasis.constr ℝ grad |>.toContinuousLinearMap\n\ndef rotprojRM' (S : ℝ³) : ℝ³ →L[ℝ] ℝ² := sorry\n\nlemma HasFDerivAt.rotproj_inner (pbar : Pose) (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) :\n    (HasFDerivAt (rotproj_inner S w) (rotproj_inner' pbar S w) pbar.innerParams) := by\n\n  have z1 : HasFDerivAt (fun x => (rotprojRM (x.ofLp 1) (x.ofLp 2) (x.ofLp 0)) S) (rotprojRM' S) pbar.innerParams := by\n    sorry\n\n  have step :\n    (rotproj_inner' pbar S w) = ((fderivInnerCLM ℝ\n            ((rotprojRM (pbar.innerParams.ofLp 1) (pbar.innerParams.ofLp 2) (pbar.innerParams.ofLp 0)) S, w)).comp\n        ((rotprojRM' S).prod 0)) := by\n    sorry\n\n  rw [step]\n  exact HasFDerivAt.inner ℝ z1 (hasFDerivAt_const w pbar.innerParams)\n\nlemma partials_helper0a {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) :\n    (fderiv ℝ (rotproj_inner_unit pc.S pc.w) pbar.innerParams) (EuclideanSpace.single 0 1) =\n    ‖pc.S‖⁻¹ * ⟪pbar.rotR' (pbar.rotM₁ pc.S), pc.w⟫  := by\n  have := pc.norm_S_ne_zero\n  change (fderiv ℝ (λ x => rotproj_inner_unit pc.S pc.w x) _) _ = _\n  unfold rotproj_inner_unit rotprojRM\n\n  convert_to (fderiv ℝ (‖pc.S‖⁻¹ • (rotproj_inner pc.S pc.w)) pbar.innerParams) (EuclideanSpace.single 0 1) = _\n  · unfold rotproj_inner rotprojRM\n    conv =>\n      rhs; arg 1; lhs; ext x; simp only [Pi.smul_apply, smul_eq_mul]\n      rw [inv_mul_eq_div]\n  have hf : DifferentiableAt ℝ (rotproj_inner pc.S pc.w) pbar.innerParams := by\n    fun_prop\n\n  rw [(hf.hasFDerivAt.const_smul ‖pc.S‖⁻¹).fderiv]\n  simp only [Fin.isValue, ContinuousLinearMap.coe_smul', Pi.smul_apply, smul_eq_mul,\n    mul_eq_mul_left_iff]\n  left\n\n  rw [HasFDerivAt.rotproj_inner pbar pc.S pc.w |>.fderiv]\n  simp [rotproj_inner']\n\nlemma partials_helper0 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) :\n    ‖pc.S‖ * nth_partial 0 pc.fu pbar.innerParams =\n    ⟪pbar.rotR' (pbar.rotM₁ pc.S), pc.w⟫ := by\n  have := pc.norm_S_ne_zero\n  simp only [nth_partial, GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu, Fin.isValue, partials_helper0a]\n  field_simp\n\nlemma partials_helper1 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) :\n    ‖pc.S‖ * nth_partial 1 pc.fu pbar.innerParams =\n    ⟪pbar.rotR (pbar.rotM₁θ pc.S), pc.w⟫ := by\n  sorry\n\nlemma partials_helper2 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) :\n    ‖pc.S‖ * nth_partial 2 pc.fu pbar.innerParams =\n    ⟪pbar.rotR (pbar.rotM₁φ pc.S), pc.w⟫ := by\n  sorry\n\nlemma partials_helper3 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) (P : ℝ³) :\n    ‖P‖ * nth_partial 0 (GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer P pc) pbar.outerParams =\n    ⟪pbar.rotM₂θ P, pc.w⟫ := by\n  sorry\n\nlemma partials_helper4 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) (P : ℝ³) :\n    ‖P‖ * nth_partial 1 (GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer P pc) pbar.outerParams =\n    ⟪pbar.rotM₂φ P, pc.w⟫ := by\n  sorry",
      "\nlemma partials_helper4 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) (P : ℝ³) :\n    ‖P‖ * nth_partial 1 (GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer P pc) pbar.outerParams =\n    ⟪pbar.rotM₂φ P, pc.w⟫ := by\n  sorry\n```\nThe `sorry` is at the end of the proof for `partials_helper4`. This lemma is supposed to establish a relationship between the norm of a point `P` and the first partial derivative (with respect to the second coordinate) of the function `fu_outer` at `P` with respect to `pbar`'s outer parameters.\n\n`fu_outer P pc` is defined as `rotproj_outer_unit S w` where `S = pbar.inner P` and `w = pc.w`. So `fu_outer P pc` is `rotproj_outer_unit (pbar.inner P) pc.w`.\nThe lemma states that `‖P‖ * nth_partial 1 (rotproj_outer_unit (pbar.inner P) pc.w) pbar.outerParams = ⟪pbar.rotM₂φ P, pc.w⟫`.\n\nTo prove this, we need to compute the partial derivative of `rotproj_outer_unit` with respect to its second argument (the point `x` in `rotproj_outer_unit x w`). This is a composition of `rotproj_outer` (which involves `pbar`'s rotation and translation matrices) and `unit` (which involves division by norm).\n\nThe strategy should be:\n1.  Use the chain rule to differentiate `unit ∘ rotproj_outer`.\n2.  The derivative of `unit(x)` with respect to `x` is `(x / ‖x‖²)`. The derivative of `rotproj_outer(x)` with respect to `x` is `pbar.rotM₂`.\n3.  So the derivative is `(pbar.rotM₂ x / ‖x‖²)`.\n4.  Evaluate at `x = pbar.inner P`.\n5.  Multiply by `‖P‖`.\n6.  Simplify to get `⟪pbar.rotM₂φ P, pc.w⟫`.\n\nLet's start the proof.\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\n```\n\nFirst, we need to import the appropriate library for working with norms, inner products, and derivatives.\n\nNow, let's define the lemma:\n```tactics\nlemma partials_helper4 {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) (P : ℝ³) :\n    ‖P‖ * nth_partial 1 (GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer P pc) pbar.outerParams =\n    inner ℝ (pbar.rotM₂φ P) (pc.w) := by\n```\n\nWe need to compute the first partial derivative of `fu_outer P pc` with respect to `pbar`'s outer parameters, then multiply by `‖P‖`, and check if it equals `inner (pbar.rotM₂φ P) (pc.w)`.\n\n`fu_outer P pc` is `rotproj_outer_unit (pbar.inner P) pc.w`.\nThis is `unit (pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P))`.\nThe partial derivative of `unit (pbar.rotM₂ x)` with respect to `x` is `(pbar.rotM₂ x / ‖pbar.rotM₂ x‖²)`.\nEvaluating at `x = pbar.inner P`, we get `(pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P) / ‖pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)‖²)`.\nMultiplying by `‖P‖`, we get `‖P‖ * (pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P) / ‖pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)‖²)`.\nThis should equal `inner (pbar.rotM₂φ P) (pc.w)`.\n\nLet's compute `pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)`.\n`pbar.inner P` is a vector in `ℝ³`. `pbar` is a `Pose`, so `pbar.rotM₂` is a `ℝ³ →L[ℝ] ℝ³` map.\n`pbar.inner P` is `P` translated to the local coordinates of the `Pose`.\n`pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)` is the rotation of `pbar.inner P` according to `pbar`'s orientation.\n\nThe goal is to show that `‖P‖ * (pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P) / ‖pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)‖²) = inner (pbar.rotM₂φ P) (pc.w)`.\n\nThis simplifies to `(pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)) * (‖P‖ / ‖pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)‖²) = inner (pbar.rotM₂φ P) (pc.w)`.\n\nThis is true if `pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P) = pbar.rotM₂φ P`. This is not necessarily true.\nWait, let's think again.\n`pbar.inner P` is `P` expressed in the local coordinates of `pbar`. `pbar.rotM₂` is the rotation matrix for `pbar`.\nSo `pbar.rotM₂ (pbar.inner P)` is `pbar`'s rotation applied to `pbar`'s local coordinates of `P`.\n`pbar.rotM₂φ P` is the third column of `pbar`'s rotation matrix `pbar.rotM₂`, applied to `P`.\n\nThis suggests the formula might be more complex.\nLet's think about `rotproj_outer`.\n`rotproj_outer x w` is `inner w (rotM x)` where `rotM x` is the rotation of `x` according to some convention. Let's assume it's `pbar`'s rotation matrices.\n`unit (rotM x)` is `rotM x / ‖rotM x‖`.\nSo `fu_outer P pc` is `un